# YAML 1.2
# https://citation-file-format.github.io/
cff-version: 1.2.0
message: >-
  If you use this software, please cite the SkillLens paper. The full
  citation will be revealed after the NeurIPS 2026 double-blind review
  period concludes.
title: >-
  SkillLens: From Task-First Evaluation to Skill-Centered Assessment
  (anonymous artifact)
authors:
  - name: "Anonymous Authors"
date-released: "2026-05-07"
url: "https://github.com/anonyy-coder/skilllens-eval"
repository-code: "https://github.com/anonyy-coder/skilllens-eval"
license: Apache-2.0
type: software
keywords:
  - large-language-models
  - agent-evaluation
  - skill-assessment
  - benchmark
  - llm-agents
abstract: >-
  SkillLens is an evaluation framework that measures the incremental
  task-completion gain that an Anthropic-style /skill markdown file
  provides to a coding or research agent, on top of a baseline run
  without the skill. It pairs scheme generation, sandboxed task
  execution via Harbor, and an LLM judge that scores both utility
  (capability gain) and security (exploitability of skill
  contents). This repository is the anonymous artifact accompanying
  the paper submitted to NeurIPS 2026.
preferred-citation:
  type: conference-paper
  authors:
    - name: "Anonymous Authors"
  title: >-
    SkillLens: From Task-First Evaluation to Skill-Centered Assessment
  year: 2026
  conference:
    name: "NeurIPS 2026 (under double-blind review)"
